    <stitle>530 and DT-466/408 Diesel Engine Service (1994) - CONNECTING RODS, PISTONS, RINGS AND SLEEVES - CONNECTING
        RODS
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>CONNECTING RODS</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="proctype" graphiccount="2">
            <title>Inspection</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Visually inspect the connecting rod bolts for nicks or damage.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Visually inspect the rod and cap mating surfaces for fretting. Replace as required.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect the connecting rod piston pin bushing for wear as follows:</para>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>WHEN LUBRICATED WITH CLEAN ENGINE OIL, THE BOLTS MUST SCREW INTO THE ROD BY HAND. IF
                            RESISTANCE IS MET, RECLEAN THE ROD THREADS AND TRY A NEW BOLT. IF A NEW BOLT DOES NOT SCREW
                            IN FREELY, THE ROD MUST BE DISCARDED. ROD THREADS CANNOT BE RETAPPED.
                        </para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Using a telescoping gauge and an outside micrometer, measure the pin bore at two
                        locations 90 degrees from one another and record the readings. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050616">6.16</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Refer to "
                        <emph type="bold">SPECIFICATIONS</emph>". If piston pin bushing I.D. exceeds minimum
                        specification, it is worn and must be replaced.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="ef1050615" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="cg11299" filename="../figcg1/CG11299.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.15.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1050616" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg2417" filename="../figeg2/EG2417.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.16.</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. Micrometer</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. Telescoping Gauge</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. Connecting Rod</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove any worn bushing using a press and a driver.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clean the connecting rod piston pin bushing bore throughly and visually inspect for
                    defects. Using a telescoping gauge and a micrometer, measure the connecting rod piston pin bushing
                    bore diameter at two locations. If out of specification, replace the connecting rod.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
